{"parse":{"title":"Beaivi","pageid":28958802,"revid":770138901,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove\" role=\"presentation\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png\" width=\"50\" height=\"39\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"512\" data-file-height=\"399\" /></a></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>needs additional citations for <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability\" title=\"Wikipedia:Verifiability\">verification</a></b>.<span class=\"hide-when-compact\"> Please help <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Beaivi&amp;action=edit\">improve this article</a> by <a href=\"/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_referencing_with_Wiki_Markup/1\" title=\"Help:Introduction to referencing with Wiki Markup/1\">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.</span>  <small><i>(May 2013)</i></small><small class=\"hide-when-compact\"><i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal\" title=\"Help:Maintenance template removal\">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a>)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:252px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Beivve_Sun_symbol.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Beivve_Sun_symbol.png/250px-Beivve_Sun_symbol.png\" width=\"250\" height=\"309\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a2/Beivve_Sun_symbol.png/375px-Beivve_Sun_symbol.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a2/Beivve_Sun_symbol.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"485\" data-file-height=\"600\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Beivve_Sun_symbol.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><b>Beivve</b> Sami <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_symbol\" title=\"Solar symbol\">Sun symbol</a></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:252px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nordic_Sami_Naero_Runic_Shaman_Drum_Mythology_from_Friis_1871.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Nordic_Sami_Naero_Runic_Shaman_Drum_Mythology_from_Friis_1871.jpg/250px-Nordic_Sami_Naero_Runic_Shaman_Drum_Mythology_from_Friis_1871.jpg\" width=\"250\" height=\"309\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Nordic_Sami_Naero_Runic_Shaman_Drum_Mythology_from_Friis_1871.jpg/375px-Nordic_Sami_Naero_Runic_Shaman_Drum_Mythology_from_Friis_1871.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a6/Nordic_Sami_Naero_Runic_Shaman_Drum_Mythology_from_Friis_1871.jpg/500px-Nordic_Sami_Naero_Runic_Shaman_Drum_Mythology_from_Friis_1871.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1566\" data-file-height=\"1937\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nordic_Sami_Naero_Runic_Shaman_Drum_Mythology_from_Friis_1871.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Sami <a href=\"/wiki/Shamanism\" title=\"Shamanism\">Shaman</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Drum\" title=\"Drum\">drum</a> found in <a href=\"/wiki/N%C3%A6r%C3%B8y,_Norway\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"N\u00e6r\u00f8y, Norway\">N\u00e6r\u00f8y, Norway</a></div></div></div>\n<p><b>Beaivi</b>, <b>Beiwe</b>, <b>Bievve</b>, <b>Beivve</b> or <b>Biejje</b>, is the <a href=\"/wiki/Sami_people\" title=\"Sami people\">Sami</a> name of the <a href=\"/wiki/Sun\" title=\"Sun\">Sun</a> or might refer to the Sami <a href=\"/wiki/Solar_deity\" title=\"Solar deity\">Sun-deity</a>. The Sami Sun-deity is mostly depicted female but sometimes also as male. In <a href=\"/wiki/S%C3%A1pmi_(area)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"S\u00e1pmi (area)\">S\u00e1pmi</a>, north of the <a href=\"/wiki/Polar_circle\" title=\"Polar circle\">Polar circle</a>, where the Sun during the winter-period, does not even reach the horizon, it is not hard to believe, that the Sun was appreciated and played a major role in the <a href=\"/wiki/Cult_(religious_practice)\" title=\"Cult (religious practice)\">cultic</a> coherence. Buorre beaivi means good day in <a href=\"/wiki/Northern_Sami_language\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Northern Sami language\">Northern S\u00e1mi</a> but doesn't have to associate with the Sun-deity.\n</p><p>Beaivi is the spring and <a href=\"/wiki/Sun_goddess\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sun goddess\">sun goddess</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Fertility\" title=\"Fertility\">fertility</a> and sanity was worshiped by the Sami, one of the indigenous peoples of <a href=\"/wiki/Fennoscandia\" title=\"Fennoscandia\">Fennoscandia</a>. \n</p><p>On the <a href=\"/wiki/Winter_solstice\" title=\"Winter solstice\">Winter solstice</a>, a white female <a href=\"/wiki/Reindeer\" title=\"Reindeer\">reindeer</a> or other white animals were <a href=\"/wiki/Sacrifice\" title=\"Sacrifice\">sacrificed</a> in honor of Beivve, to ensure that she returned to the world and put an end to the long winter season. At the time of the year when the Sun was returning, <a href=\"/wiki/Butter\" title=\"Butter\">butter</a> (which melts in the sunshine) was smeared on the doorposts, as a sacrifice to Beivve, so that she could gain strength during her convalescence and go higher and higher in the sky. At <a href=\"/wiki/Summer_solstice\" title=\"Summer solstice\">Summer solstice</a>, people made sun-rings out of leaves and pinned them up in her honor. At these occasions, they also ate butter as a <a href=\"/wiki/Sacred\" title=\"Sacred\">sacral</a> meal. \n</p><p>Beivve was often accompanied by her daughter, Beaivi-nieida (the sun maiden) in an enclosure of reindeer <a href=\"/wiki/Antler\" title=\"Antler\">antlers</a>.\n</p><p>Beivve brought fertility back to the <a href=\"/wiki/Arctic\" title=\"Arctic\">Arctic</a> region, she made the plants grow, so that the reindeer flourished and reproduced, and brought wealth and prosperity to the humans.\n</p><p>At the time of the year when Beivve returned, <a href=\"/wiki/Prayer\" title=\"Prayer\">prayers</a> were made for the people who were mentally ill.  The Sami considered - quite correctly - that madness in the shape of psychoses and depressions were provoked by the lack of sunshine and light during the dark winter-season.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In Sami myth, she travels with her daughter Beaivi-nieida through the sky in an enclosure covered by reindeer bones, bringing green plants back to the winter earth for the reindeer to eat. She was also called upon to restore the mental health of those who went insane because of the continual darkness of the long winter.\n</p><p>Worshipers of Beaivi used to sacrifice white female animals, and thread the meat onto sticks which they bend into rings and tie with bright ribbons. They also cover their doorposts with butter so Beaivi can eat it and begin her journey once again. This is called the Festival of Beaivi. \n</p><p>She is associated with the fertility of plants and animals, in particular reindeer.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Beaivi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Sami_shamanism\" title=\"Sami shamanism\">Sami shamanism</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Beaivi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.tjatsi.fo/?side=491b24523f05ea96689d93e856f99618\">www.tjatsi.fo</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Beaivi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.schooloftheseasons.com/decdays2.html\">December 2003 Holidays- School of Seasons</a></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2269\nCached time: 20180917004126\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.056 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.078 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 166/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 4086/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 78/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 1/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 411/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.020/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 836 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   57.748      1 -total\n 79.26%   45.772      1 